1
00:00:01,580 --> 00:00:04,800
Dovzhenko Film Studios

2
00:00:04,880 --> 00:00:09,520
Ukrainian Ministry of Culture

3
00:00:09,600 --> 00:00:12,520
'Veselka' Creative Group

4
00:00:12,600 --> 00:00:22,900
The Seventh Route

5
00:01:43,943 --> 00:01:53,943
<i>Don't look for me. Yours, Nadiia
[Nadiia literally meaning "Hope"]</i>

6
00:02:09,600 --> 00:02:11,180
Hello.

7
00:02:12,100 --> 00:02:14,180
I'm on my way.

8
00:02:23,020 --> 00:02:25,040
Oh God...

9
00:02:33,500 --> 00:02:36,940
<i>Poems, by Danylo Prytuliuk</i>

10
00:02:57,650 --> 00:02:59,367
Happy birthday, mom.

11
00:02:59,657 --> 00:03:01,340
Good morning.

12
00:03:05,042 --> 00:03:09,680
It's not morning yet for you,
but over here it's your birthday already.

13
00:03:09,760 --> 00:03:12,680
Over here, in your city.

14
00:03:12,760 --> 00:03:15,680
Here's my greetings and here's my gift.

15
00:03:15,760 --> 00:03:17,080
This very morning.

16
00:03:17,160 --> 00:03:18,860
Those streets, familiar to you.

17
00:03:19,111 --> 00:03:22,111
Those majestic hills.

18
00:03:37,998 --> 00:03:39,400
Alright.

19
00:04:03,460 --> 00:04:05,020
Here, kitty kitty!

20
00:04:05,360 --> 00:04:07,330
Here, kitty kitty!

21
00:04:46,900 --> 00:04:50,480
Don't freak out.
As you can see, I'm currently in Kyiv.

22
00:04:51,215 --> 00:04:53,907
Unfortunately,
I know so little about it.

23
00:04:54,575 --> 00:04:59,341
It's precisely because you keep
your secrets to yourself

24
00:04:59,620 --> 00:05:01,499
that I'm drawn towards them.

25
00:05:01,580 --> 00:05:04,580
Towards your first life,
your native city.

26
00:05:05,072 --> 00:05:06,981
I don't know
how much it has changed,

27
00:05:07,061 --> 00:05:10,540
and if those alleys and boulevards
still look familiar to you.

28
00:05:11,280 --> 00:05:13,660
But I hope my gift pleases you.

29
00:05:28,328 --> 00:05:31,040
This is especially for my mom,

30
00:05:34,540 --> 00:05:36,920
from your native city,
your loving daughter.

31
00:05:38,930 --> 00:05:40,520
Well, alright then.

32
00:05:41,727 --> 00:05:44,220
Here, kitty kitty...

33
00:05:50,640 --> 00:05:52,180
Nadiia,

34
00:05:53,141 --> 00:05:55,742
I did not want to wake you up,

35
00:05:56,560 --> 00:05:58,352
you slept so peacefully.

36
00:05:59,660 --> 00:06:01,180
Breakfast is ready.

37
00:06:02,820 --> 00:06:04,116
I will call you

38
00:06:04,480 --> 00:06:05,742
from work.

39
00:06:06,300 --> 00:06:07,840
Yours, Danylo.

40
00:07:08,188 --> 00:07:12,594
<i>Don't look for me. Yours, Nadiia</i>

41
00:07:13,720 --> 00:07:17,180
Sorry I didn't tell you about my trip.
It's a surprise.

42
00:07:17,593 --> 00:07:20,141
I am as adventurous as you once were.

43
00:07:20,760 --> 00:07:24,164
I looked through all the letters
you've ever received from Kyiv.

44
00:07:24,640 --> 00:07:28,820
Honestly, I would've read them,
but I don't know Ukrainian.

45
00:07:29,780 --> 00:07:34,620
At least I wrote all the addresses down.

46
00:07:35,800 --> 00:07:37,840
I don't know what they mean to you,

47
00:07:38,292 --> 00:07:40,216
but I'm visiting all of them.

48
00:07:43,170 --> 00:07:44,220
It's peculiar.

49
00:07:44,300 --> 00:07:48,020
One of those addresses
is a cycling track.

50
00:07:48,583 --> 00:07:49,843
And on top of that...

51
00:07:49,924 --> 00:07:53,204
...that's where most of your letters
came from.

52
00:07:54,100 --> 00:07:57,310
Does cycling mean something to you?

53
00:07:59,200 --> 00:08:00,217
Alright.

54
00:08:00,540 --> 00:08:03,700
This one beats even the cycling track.

55
00:08:05,220 --> 00:08:07,558
Were you friends with all
these renowned people?

56
00:08:08,800 --> 00:08:11,737
You have no idea how surprised I am.

57
00:08:35,680 --> 00:08:38,600
<i>Pavlo Shans, Prof.
[Shans literally meaning "Chance"]</i>

58
00:08:38,680 --> 00:08:42,220
Oh, how I want to open this door,
apartment 64.

59
00:08:43,380 --> 00:08:47,900
Envelopes from this address
were the thickest.

60
00:08:47,980 --> 00:08:50,980
I'm absolutely sure you've
visited this place.

61
00:08:51,380 --> 00:08:53,060
You're familiar with this stairway,

62
00:08:53,317 --> 00:08:54,542
this alleyway...

63
00:09:53,740 --> 00:09:57,167
<i>Honcharna street, 7</i>

64
00:09:58,800 --> 00:10:02,320
This address is the most mysterious one.

65
00:10:02,823 --> 00:10:05,320
This building's in ruins.

66
00:10:05,820 --> 00:10:10,020
But what really confounds me
is the letters.

67
00:10:10,100 --> 00:10:12,460
You know what I want to ask you.

68
00:10:12,720 --> 00:10:16,307
I want to know what's in those
three letters sent from Honcharna street.

69
00:10:18,820 --> 00:10:19,860
Danylo Prytuliuk!

70
00:10:19,940 --> 00:10:22,140
What the hell's keeping you?
I'm tired of waiting.

71
00:10:22,221 --> 00:10:23,746
There was no bus. I had to walk.

72
00:10:23,833 --> 00:10:25,620
What's with the forehead?

73
00:10:25,700 --> 00:10:28,040
- I slipped, changing the lightbulb.
- You look terrible.

74
00:10:28,120 --> 00:10:29,900
- I'm Danylo.
- Olia.

75
00:10:29,980 --> 00:10:31,540
What's for today?

76
00:10:31,620 --> 00:10:33,880
Americans on tour.

77
00:10:33,960 --> 00:10:38,000
You mess the tour up, you're paying
with your own money, got it?

78
00:10:38,089 --> 00:10:39,500
- Got it.
- Hit the road!

79
00:10:58,208 --> 00:11:00,318
They are asking which route
we are doing today.

80
00:11:00,398 --> 00:11:02,420
- Which one did we do yesterday?
- The sixth.

81
00:11:02,500 --> 00:11:03,895
There's no seventh route.

82
00:11:03,975 --> 00:11:05,161
It's paid for already.

83
00:11:05,786 --> 00:11:09,450
Oh, come on now!
What am I to do?

84
00:11:20,750 --> 00:11:21,499
Hear him?

85
00:11:21,580 --> 00:11:22,800
What does he want?

86
00:11:22,880 --> 00:11:25,142
He wants to hear the tongue.
Can you do that?

87
00:11:25,222 --> 00:11:27,042
Will they understand?

88
00:11:27,447 --> 00:11:29,580
They want to
hear their ancestors' tongue.

89
00:11:29,660 --> 00:11:31,360
Why does he talk in English then?

90
00:11:31,455 --> 00:11:33,115
He only knows his English.

91
00:11:48,080 --> 00:11:50,973
This is their first time.
They aren't learning Ukrainian yet.

92
00:11:51,054 --> 00:11:53,071
They just want to hear how it sounds.

93
00:11:55,880 --> 00:11:58,580
He's asking what
the seventh route is about.

94
00:11:58,920 --> 00:11:59,980
The seventh route?

95
00:12:03,660 --> 00:12:05,331
Oh well, ladies and gentlemen.

96
00:12:05,632 --> 00:12:07,230
It's something to behold.

97
00:12:16,655 --> 00:12:17,690
Follow me.

98
00:12:25,760 --> 00:12:26,620
Ladies and gentlemen,

99
00:12:26,700 --> 00:12:28,905
today we are following
the footsteps of an artist.

100
00:12:28,985 --> 00:12:32,260
Once you've encountered his art,
you'll remember the name forever.

101
00:12:46,920 --> 00:12:48,520
Today we are...

102
00:12:49,060 --> 00:12:50,960
I'm repeating myself.

103
00:12:52,100 --> 00:12:53,080
Ladies and gentlemen.

104
00:12:53,540 --> 00:12:56,540
He spent his younger days here.

105
00:12:56,620 --> 00:12:58,200
Our great poet...

106
00:12:58,720 --> 00:13:00,280
He's our great...

107
00:13:01,680 --> 00:13:03,280
Sorry, my voice is trembling.

108
00:13:09,800 --> 00:13:11,560
What I'm about to tell you

109
00:13:11,640 --> 00:13:13,560
is the story of life and death

110
00:13:14,200 --> 00:13:15,840
of a poet, and a friend of mine.

111
00:13:16,760 --> 00:13:18,840
Danylo Fedorovych...

112
00:13:20,460 --> 00:13:21,840
Prytuliuk.

113
00:13:51,055 --> 00:13:54,924
<i>Inhale, like that! Exhale! Again!</i>

114
00:13:57,833 --> 00:13:59,519
<i>And reach upwards!</i>

115
00:14:01,050 --> 00:14:02,786
<i>Now in front of you!</i>

116
00:14:05,862 --> 00:14:07,588
<i>Up, back, down!</i>

117
00:14:08,073 --> 00:14:09,250
<i>Now the other shoulder!</i>

118
00:14:10,736 --> 00:14:12,500
<i>Great, now the back muscles!</i>

119
00:14:14,366 --> 00:14:15,583
<i>Wide steps!</i>

120
00:14:17,375 --> 00:14:19,088
<i>Back straight, stomach - tight!</i>

121
00:14:19,500 --> 00:14:21,826
<i>Four, three, two...</i>

122
00:14:21,906 --> 00:14:23,406
<i>Now add arm movement!</i>

123
00:14:24,906 --> 00:14:26,906
<i>Great, now walk in one place.</i>

124
00:14:42,000 --> 00:14:44,160
You and Tolik went insane yesterday.

125
00:14:44,240 --> 00:14:46,539
How is he?

126
00:14:46,656 --> 00:14:48,667
Did you deliver the paint yesterday?

127
00:14:49,800 --> 00:14:51,480
Do you know Prytuliuk, the poet?

128
00:14:51,560 --> 00:14:52,700
I don't.

129
00:14:53,580 --> 00:14:55,340
Here he is, hat and sunglasses.

130
00:14:59,287 --> 00:15:01,427
<i>Back straight,
without turning your shoulders -</i>

131
00:15:01,507 --> 00:15:02,698
<i>Like this!</i>

132
00:15:08,186 --> 00:15:09,542
<i>Add some arm movement!</i>

133
00:15:14,520 --> 00:15:18,070
The food's out on the balcony.

134
00:15:18,150 --> 00:15:19,410
Don't worry.

135
00:15:24,133 --> 00:15:26,211
<i>And again, from the beginning!</i>

136
00:15:52,240 --> 00:15:56,280
A salty rain had graced the city,
Dnipro now has...

137
00:15:57,820 --> 00:15:59,232
...a touch of salt.

138
00:16:01,880 --> 00:16:04,280
See: in a dried-up salty puddle

139
00:16:05,400 --> 00:16:08,080
Reflection of a star of gold.

140
00:16:08,911 --> 00:16:09,760
No, no.

141
00:16:10,100 --> 00:16:13,900
See: in an oversalted puddle
Reflection of a star of salt.

142
00:16:13,980 --> 00:16:16,420
The night's a roof above the town.

143
00:16:16,500 --> 00:16:19,500
The Milky Way is raining down.

144
00:16:20,820 --> 00:16:23,600
One star is left, and only one.

145
00:17:03,280 --> 00:17:05,020
There, under the rooftop...

146
00:17:05,100 --> 00:17:06,300
is where the poet lived.

147
00:17:09,340 --> 00:17:10,605
And over there...

148
00:17:10,740 --> 00:17:12,100
his star was shining.

149
00:17:15,113 --> 00:17:16,311
Ladies and gentlemen.

150
00:17:16,391 --> 00:17:18,520
The next exhibit is very unique.

151
00:17:18,600 --> 00:17:19,714
Let's go.

152
00:17:48,760 --> 00:17:54,320
There used to be
a huge fence right there.

153
00:17:56,740 --> 00:18:02,020
I was 12 when I first
saw Danylo drunk.

154
00:18:07,980 --> 00:18:09,550
We were friends already by then.

155
00:18:09,630 --> 00:18:12,630
I have no idea
how and why that happened.

156
00:18:13,160 --> 00:18:17,140
I saw Danylo right there.

157
00:18:18,125 --> 00:18:20,466
He said to me, come over and see.

158
00:18:20,755 --> 00:18:22,011
And brought me...

159
00:18:22,091 --> 00:18:23,085
...here.

160
00:18:23,165 --> 00:18:24,805
Here was the fence,

161
00:18:25,680 --> 00:18:26,880
here, an old shed,

162
00:18:26,960 --> 00:18:30,535
and there was a narrow
gap in between.

163
00:18:30,615 --> 00:18:31,700
Allow me.

164
00:18:33,780 --> 00:18:36,120
He pushed me...

165
00:18:37,020 --> 00:18:38,449
right into the gap.

166
00:18:38,529 --> 00:18:39,552
Allow me.

167
00:18:41,460 --> 00:18:42,880
This very gap.

168
00:18:49,160 --> 00:18:50,560
He lit a match.

169
00:18:51,723 --> 00:18:53,723
Does anyone have a match?

170
00:19:01,150 --> 00:19:02,966
And on this fence...

171
00:19:03,546 --> 00:19:05,165
for the first time ever...

172
00:19:05,357 --> 00:19:07,860
he wrote a poem.

173
00:19:09,083 --> 00:19:10,184
How does it go again?

174
00:19:10,302 --> 00:19:11,280
She's all...

175
00:19:11,360 --> 00:19:12,360
It'll come to me.

176
00:19:16,290 --> 00:19:17,240
She's all...

177
00:19:17,676 --> 00:19:21,670
...grown-up, if not yet wise,
She came of age, she's in full bloom.

178
00:19:22,220 --> 00:19:24,440
She's not too sure,
She's not too tired.

179
00:19:24,520 --> 00:19:26,180
She has desires.

180
00:19:26,260 --> 00:19:30,310
Her face is one
Big question mark,

181
00:19:31,820 --> 00:19:35,500
She's crying shyly
In the dark.

182
00:19:53,324 --> 00:19:58,011
<i>♬ If your so-called friends ♬</i>

183
00:19:59,460 --> 00:20:03,703
<i>♬ Are telling you what to do - ♬</i>

184
00:20:05,703 --> 00:20:07,286
<i>♬ Listen, ♬</i>

185
00:20:08,414 --> 00:20:15,865
<i>♬ Go with your true desires. ♬</i>

186
00:20:17,623 --> 00:20:22,756
<i>♬ Go with the crows, crow just like them, ♬</i>

187
00:20:22,836 --> 00:20:27,120
<i>♬ Go with the crows, crow just like them. ♬</i>

188
00:20:56,492 --> 00:21:04,154
<i>♬ "Don't look her way",
my friends would say. ♬</i>

189
00:21:05,221 --> 00:21:12,966
<i>♬ "She is too young still,
she won't understand". ♬</i>

190
00:21:14,335 --> 00:21:18,080
<i>♬ Go with the crows, crow just like them. ♬</i>

191
00:21:18,672 --> 00:21:22,866
<i>♬ Go with the crows, crow just like them. ♬</i>

192
00:21:31,160 --> 00:21:35,182
<i>♬ I followed their advice, ♬</i>

193
00:21:35,262 --> 00:21:38,004
<i>♬ I left her. ♬</i>

194
00:21:39,283 --> 00:21:46,588
<i>♬ Tears were rolling down her face. ♬</i>

195
00:21:47,381 --> 00:21:51,185
<i>♬ Go with the crows, crow just like them. ♬</i>

196
00:21:51,265 --> 00:21:55,136
<i>♬ Go with the crows, crow just like them. ♬</i>

197
00:23:26,020 --> 00:23:28,918
He dedicated the poem to his sister.

198
00:23:29,680 --> 00:23:32,600
Eventually, once the seventh
route becomes official...

199
00:23:32,900 --> 00:23:38,580
the tourists will visit the plaques,
the Prytuliuk Museum, his school.

200
00:23:38,660 --> 00:23:42,080
But what's a museum
compared to this fence?

201
00:23:42,440 --> 00:23:43,980
Or to Sukhohryz.

202
00:23:44,060 --> 00:23:47,060
Sukhohryz, the poet's nemesis.

203
00:23:52,520 --> 00:23:53,760
What's his question?

204
00:23:53,840 --> 00:23:56,120
They want to know more about Sukhohryz.

205
00:23:56,200 --> 00:23:57,860
Later.

206
00:23:57,940 --> 00:24:00,860
Now, we'll meet the poet's
penultimate wife.

207
00:24:00,940 --> 00:24:01,961
No...

208
00:24:02,041 --> 00:24:05,520
We'll start with the latest wife.
But I would have to make a call.

209
00:24:15,620 --> 00:24:16,440
Vira.

210
00:24:16,520 --> 00:24:18,070
Is Nadiia there?

211
00:24:18,150 --> 00:24:20,830
Tell her I was looking for her.
Give her my love.

212
00:24:21,880 --> 00:24:27,660
Danylo's philosophy was simple and wise.

213
00:24:27,740 --> 00:24:29,860
A philosophy thousands of years old.

214
00:24:44,200 --> 00:24:47,200
- Full contact.
- Don't get in the way.

215
00:24:50,420 --> 00:24:53,620
He told me once...
I'm paraphrasing of course.

216
00:24:59,500 --> 00:25:02,740
"It seems to me, he said,

217
00:25:03,940 --> 00:25:07,640
that almost everyone treats
their life as a rehearsal.

218
00:25:09,240 --> 00:25:12,608
We're abusing the luxury of
coming to the rehearsal unprepared.

219
00:25:12,780 --> 00:25:14,540
We've not learned the script yet.

220
00:25:14,620 --> 00:25:17,060
We don't know our scenic partners well.

221
00:25:18,150 --> 00:25:21,190
We use the sets which are left over

222
00:25:21,906 --> 00:25:23,298
from someone else's performance.

223
00:25:23,540 --> 00:25:25,209
The sets are dusty and deteriorating,

224
00:25:25,290 --> 00:25:27,569
and we're in no hurry to put
some fresh paint on them.

225
00:25:27,650 --> 00:25:30,380
We wait for
someone else to do it for us.

226
00:25:30,830 --> 00:25:32,500
We drink our tea from broken cups

227
00:25:32,940 --> 00:25:35,210
and wait till one day, God willing,

228
00:25:35,880 --> 00:25:37,333
the rehearsal will end,

229
00:25:37,464 --> 00:25:39,403
and we'll perform
at the opening night.

230
00:25:39,560 --> 00:25:42,880
Here's where the actual life starts.

231
00:25:42,960 --> 00:25:44,980
But there will be no opening night.

232
00:25:45,080 --> 00:25:47,158
We wait in vain."

233
00:25:49,100 --> 00:25:52,240
I know this chair, I ate this bread,

234
00:25:52,320 --> 00:25:54,100
I made some babies on that bed;

235
00:25:54,180 --> 00:25:56,330
In fringe's depths, the cold's residing,

236
00:25:56,620 --> 00:25:58,961
There's
vacuum cleaner's somewhere, hiding.

237
00:25:59,041 --> 00:26:01,680
The ice paints white
the bottle's glass,

238
00:26:01,760 --> 00:26:03,155
In sour spirits, I - alas! -

239
00:26:03,236 --> 00:26:06,500
Reach for my trusty wishing well,

240
00:26:06,580 --> 00:26:11,860
With rhymes too intricate too tell.
I've rhymed my dreams with vile advice,

241
00:26:11,940 --> 00:26:14,320
Bad jokes and rotten luck - with lies,

242
00:26:14,780 --> 00:26:17,240
Rhymes of self-pity and disgust,

243
00:26:17,320 --> 00:26:19,500
My solemn thoughts which no one asked.

244
00:26:46,525 --> 00:26:49,063
<i>♬ I'm away to search
for the latest fashions, ♬</i>

245
00:26:49,143 --> 00:26:52,433
<i>♬ I won't find any around here. ♬</i>

246
00:26:52,513 --> 00:26:55,120
<i>♬ I don't know what I'm looking for
all alone, ♬</i>

247
00:26:55,670 --> 00:26:58,741
<i>♬ I just want to hear some singing. ♬</i>

248
00:27:02,701 --> 00:27:05,350
<i>♬ Do you own anything? ♬</i>

249
00:27:05,430 --> 00:27:08,771
<i>♬ Hear, what are you selling? ♬</i>

250
00:27:08,851 --> 00:27:13,369
<i>♬ I can buy it all from you. ♬</i>

251
00:27:19,097 --> 00:27:23,512
<i>♬ I ended up
same way I started out. ♬</i>

252
00:27:55,291 --> 00:28:01,015
<i>♬ Listen,
Queen's not dead. ♬</i>

253
00:28:12,670 --> 00:28:15,660
<i>Missing</i>

254
00:28:22,460 --> 00:28:25,764
Ira, it's me. Is Nadiia home yet?

255
00:28:26,667 --> 00:28:27,962
She hasn't called, either?

256
00:28:28,042 --> 00:28:31,700
Tell her I called from work.
Give her my love.

257
00:28:31,780 --> 00:28:33,677
Bye-bye.

258
00:28:41,680 --> 00:28:43,100
So?

259
00:28:43,180 --> 00:28:44,383
Good for you?

260
00:28:46,601 --> 00:28:48,841
Bring something more colorful.

261
00:28:48,922 --> 00:28:50,040
He's picky.

262
00:29:41,020 --> 00:29:43,540
Ladies and gentlemen!
Another exhibit coming up.

263
00:29:43,620 --> 00:29:46,620
This key is of huge importance.

264
00:29:47,340 --> 00:29:50,520
It opens the poet's desk drawer.

265
00:29:56,860 --> 00:30:02,520
Everyone agrees that after Prytuliuk died,
his manuscripts were stolen...

266
00:30:02,600 --> 00:30:05,200
since the drawer was found empty.

267
00:30:05,280 --> 00:30:09,245
All was gone but for the poet's last will,
in which he left the table to me.

268
00:30:11,820 --> 00:30:14,405
They reached out to me
from the Prytuliuk Museum...

269
00:30:14,800 --> 00:30:17,040
looking to get the desk.
Good luck with that.

270
00:30:17,920 --> 00:30:19,960
They're aligned with Sukhohryz.

271
00:30:20,040 --> 00:30:23,400
Sukhohryz who destroyed the poet's
first printed work.

272
00:30:23,840 --> 00:30:25,600
We're about to see the desk.

273
00:30:27,660 --> 00:30:30,310
Oksana's place? No, thanks.

274
00:30:32,260 --> 00:30:34,240
No one's home, I called.

275
00:30:35,580 --> 00:30:38,420
Though if you see Oksana, honk the horn.

276
00:30:38,822 --> 00:30:41,040
Danylo, you're a horse's ass,
you know that?

277
00:30:53,800 --> 00:30:56,800
Can we learn more about Sukhohryz?

278
00:30:57,097 --> 00:30:58,357
You may.

279
00:30:58,773 --> 00:31:00,440
Sukhohryz ordered...

280
00:31:00,520 --> 00:31:03,440
for the whole first edition
to go into the recycling facility.

281
00:31:03,520 --> 00:31:07,740
The editor, Nina Shans,
kept several copies hidden.

282
00:31:08,572 --> 00:31:13,346
Danylo was lucky: Nina had close ties
to the communist party.

283
00:31:13,427 --> 00:31:14,330
Come in.

284
00:31:17,840 --> 00:31:20,320
I have a key, and there's nobody home.

285
00:31:31,937 --> 00:31:32,998
Don't sweat.

286
00:31:40,240 --> 00:31:41,660
Come in.

287
00:31:42,860 --> 00:31:44,660
Some more exhibits

288
00:31:50,372 --> 00:31:52,325
which will go to the Prytuliuk Museum.

289
00:31:56,360 --> 00:31:59,380
He was the best cyclist
of his neighborhood.

290
00:32:03,460 --> 00:32:06,680
And here, ladies and gentlemen,
is what we came here for.

291
00:32:11,160 --> 00:32:14,880
The famous desk,
and its famous drawer.

292
00:32:14,960 --> 00:32:18,600
Full of rhymes and inspiration.

293
00:32:19,380 --> 00:32:21,600
<i>Take your trash away,
I'm changing locks.</i>

294
00:32:24,560 --> 00:32:26,080
It's for you.

295
00:32:34,800 --> 00:32:37,260
They want to know more
about the political ties.

296
00:32:37,673 --> 00:32:39,973
Yes, there's a poem about it.

297
00:32:40,620 --> 00:32:41,800
There's a poem.

298
00:32:41,973 --> 00:32:43,433
Just a moment.

299
00:32:45,480 --> 00:32:48,740
One day, when I die,
Will I burn in hell?

300
00:32:48,820 --> 00:32:52,460
Weather's warm and dry.
Thus, it's hard to tell.

301
00:32:54,000 --> 00:32:55,080
6 am...

302
00:32:56,660 --> 00:32:57,650
6 am...

303
00:32:59,487 --> 00:33:00,887
6 am...

304
00:33:00,968 --> 00:33:05,683
The architect is Rastrelli. What a shame.
[pun: Rastrelli sounds like "was executed"]

305
00:33:05,980 --> 00:33:07,600
6 am - no kidding! -

306
00:33:07,680 --> 00:33:09,160
Stars are shining bright.

307
00:33:09,240 --> 00:33:12,640
I am in the city.
Foggy is my mind.

308
00:33:18,150 --> 00:33:23,162
<i>♬ I'm no fool, I can tell
I drink way too much vodka! ♬</i>

309
00:33:37,322 --> 00:33:41,540
<i>♬ My neighbour had a drink with me -
I think I love her now. ♬</i>

310
00:33:41,998 --> 00:33:47,011
<i>♬ Help a guy out, please -
pour me another one! ♬</i>

311
00:33:47,091 --> 00:33:51,872
<i>♬ I'm no fool, I can tell
I drink way too much vodka! ♬</i>

312
00:33:54,860 --> 00:33:56,720
Interesting.

313
00:34:00,800 --> 00:34:02,840
Let's go.

314
00:34:07,320 --> 00:34:08,960
Just some asshole.

315
00:34:13,520 --> 00:34:15,740
Call me.

316
00:34:16,368 --> 00:34:18,828
<i>♬ Oh, I want a rich woman! ♬</i>

317
00:34:20,930 --> 00:34:23,362
<i>♬ Oh, I want a woman
of such and such sort. ♬</i>

318
00:34:25,448 --> 00:34:29,500
<i>♬ I'm so glad we've met each other! ♬</i>

319
00:34:33,203 --> 00:34:35,638
Don't fall asleep.

320
00:34:43,739 --> 00:34:46,497
Cigarettes.
Bilomorkanal!

321
00:34:50,380 --> 00:34:51,920
He doesn't bite.

322
00:34:52,000 --> 00:34:55,000
Thank you.

323
00:35:05,400 --> 00:35:07,998
Nina Shans!

324
00:35:08,720 --> 00:35:10,748
You too?

325
00:35:13,704 --> 00:35:14,914
Let's go.

326
00:35:18,482 --> 00:35:21,026
<i>♬ I want a rich woman! ♬</i>

327
00:35:23,080 --> 00:35:25,290
<i>♬ Oh, I want a woman
of such and such sort. ♬</i>

328
00:35:28,123 --> 00:35:32,396
<i>♬ How fortunate that we've met! ♬</i>

329
00:35:40,310 --> 00:35:42,047
Did this poem's manuscript survive?

330
00:35:42,128 --> 00:35:44,348
Sukhohryz took care of it.

331
00:35:44,997 --> 00:35:48,622
Tell her the woman in the car
saved Danylo's life.

332
00:35:49,020 --> 00:35:50,700
It was Nina Shans.

333
00:35:58,900 --> 00:36:02,540
Liudmyla, is Nadiia with you?

334
00:36:03,680 --> 00:36:05,130
She went where?

335
00:36:05,210 --> 00:36:06,600
How do you mean, airport?

336
00:36:07,333 --> 00:36:11,380
What do you mean, flew home?
If I'd known, I wouldn't have called.

337
00:36:12,800 --> 00:36:15,940
Perhaps you
bought her the ticket too, huh?

338
00:36:17,865 --> 00:36:20,600
Thanks. Thanks a bunch.

339
00:36:20,680 --> 00:36:23,680
I have no time to chat with you.

340
00:36:24,230 --> 00:36:28,872
Tell me. Wait, tell me,
what's the Lviv city code?

341
00:36:30,665 --> 00:36:32,335
Ok. Close it down.

342
00:36:41,196 --> 00:36:43,170
Are you about to head off?

343
00:36:43,250 --> 00:36:44,048
Yes.

344
00:36:44,129 --> 00:36:45,769
Wait a second.

345
00:36:46,520 --> 00:36:49,160
Get out of there. Get out.

346
00:36:52,820 --> 00:36:53,880
Let's go.

347
00:37:05,380 --> 00:37:07,220
I know a poem too.

348
00:37:07,640 --> 00:37:09,580
One of Prytuliuk's earliest.

349
00:37:09,660 --> 00:37:11,098
Olia, translate, please.

350
00:37:11,540 --> 00:37:14,868
I don't pass my in-law's house
Without doing something nice.

351
00:37:14,948 --> 00:37:19,533
Pull my... nose... out, tease a little,
Then I moon her with my... ear.

352
00:37:19,880 --> 00:37:22,680
They ask where did all the drafts
and manuscripts go.

353
00:37:22,760 --> 00:37:24,583
There weren't any drafts.

354
00:37:25,271 --> 00:37:28,600
Danylo showed me the desk drawer once.
Empty.

355
00:37:29,263 --> 00:37:31,520
Still, he kept
a key with him at all times.

356
00:37:31,600 --> 00:37:34,520
He told me
he keeps the ideas in the drawer.

357
00:37:34,600 --> 00:37:37,280
That tragic day,
he had the key with him as well.

358
00:37:37,360 --> 00:37:38,440
Tragic?

359
00:37:40,820 --> 00:37:42,170
He drowned.

360
00:37:42,735 --> 00:37:44,520
How did it happen?

361
00:37:44,600 --> 00:37:45,960
I'll be damned.

362
00:37:46,040 --> 00:37:47,701
He was saving a child.

363
00:37:47,781 --> 00:37:49,280
And did he succeed?

364
00:37:49,360 --> 00:37:51,880
Yes, this boy is 25 now.

365
00:37:51,960 --> 00:37:53,820
Last two years, in jail.

366
00:37:53,900 --> 00:37:55,180
Wow. For what?

367
00:37:55,260 --> 00:37:57,320
For robbing a cash truck.

368
00:37:58,055 --> 00:37:59,560
Terrible.

369
00:37:59,640 --> 00:38:00,860
What happened then?

370
00:38:00,940 --> 00:38:03,540
- To the cash truck?
- No, no, Prytuliuk.

371
00:38:04,460 --> 00:38:07,690
- Some said he couldn't swim...
- What's the hurry!

372
00:38:10,400 --> 00:38:13,471
Some say he couldn't swim.
Some say he was too drunk.

373
00:38:13,744 --> 00:38:15,588
Some say someone
"helped" him drown.

374
00:38:15,920 --> 00:38:20,520
Only Nina Shans knows the truth.
She was with him that day.

375
00:38:20,920 --> 00:38:22,520
After that she went cuckoo.

376
00:38:24,408 --> 00:38:27,480
She spends
every summer in an institution.

377
00:38:29,460 --> 00:38:31,280
God damn. Fuck.

378
00:38:32,000 --> 00:38:34,860
Pardon. Pardon. Two minutes.

379
00:38:34,940 --> 00:38:35,960
What happened?

380
00:38:36,040 --> 00:38:38,320
The damned pump.

381
00:38:39,760 --> 00:38:41,000
The pump!

382
00:38:41,080 --> 00:38:42,900
Help me out here, Bohdan.

383
00:38:44,880 --> 00:38:45,930
Listen.

384
00:38:46,594 --> 00:38:49,434
You translate in a peculiar way.

385
00:38:49,619 --> 00:38:51,820
How do you manage the verse?

386
00:38:52,193 --> 00:38:53,542
It's gotta be hard.

387
00:38:53,622 --> 00:38:54,825
Not really.

388
00:38:55,052 --> 00:38:56,820
It was all in my university thesis.

389
00:38:56,900 --> 00:38:58,044
What thesis?

390
00:38:58,780 --> 00:39:01,675
Ukrainian folksongs in English.

391
00:40:49,560 --> 00:40:57,600
(reads incoherent poetry)

392
00:41:08,320 --> 00:41:13,200
This country brought me pain.
Brought me pain.

393
00:41:24,286 --> 00:41:26,075
<i>Pavlov Psychiatric Hospital</i>

394
00:41:26,155 --> 00:41:27,980
<i>A Study of History, by Arnold Toynbee</i>

395
00:41:28,060 --> 00:41:29,137
Lukian.

396
00:41:29,540 --> 00:41:31,849
Oh, hello. You came back?

397
00:41:32,302 --> 00:41:33,339
Have you seen Nina?

398
00:41:33,419 --> 00:41:36,350
Nina, Nina, Nina, Nina...
She ran away two days ago.

399
00:41:36,903 --> 00:41:38,590
- The search is on.
- The search is on?

400
00:41:38,671 --> 00:41:40,131
The search is on. Do come in.

401
00:41:44,960 --> 00:41:48,336
She's not in there, she was sent home.
She got better.

402
00:41:53,440 --> 00:41:56,020
Imagine, bringing flowers to a lunatic.

403
00:41:56,100 --> 00:41:57,880
Damn you all.

404
00:41:57,960 --> 00:42:01,940
If I knew what this day will turn into,
like hell I would've shown up.

405
00:42:05,573 --> 00:42:06,680
Well, there you are.

406
00:42:06,760 --> 00:42:08,980
They say your tour is no good.

407
00:42:09,060 --> 00:42:10,280
What's not to like?

408
00:42:10,360 --> 00:42:15,680
They are tired of empty drawers,
absent people and missing fences.

409
00:42:15,760 --> 00:42:16,800
What does she want to see then?

410
00:42:16,880 --> 00:42:19,500
Something substantial,
to film and to show at home.

411
00:42:20,420 --> 00:42:21,440
Oh.

412
00:42:22,260 --> 00:42:25,720
I can show you the poet's peasant house,
but it's in the Zone.

413
00:42:25,800 --> 00:42:26,749
In the Zone?

414
00:42:26,830 --> 00:42:28,064
Chornobyl zone.

415
00:42:28,780 --> 00:42:31,160
And who's gonna let us in there?

416
00:42:32,100 --> 00:42:32,927
No one.

417
00:42:33,008 --> 00:42:35,618
We'll go to Feofaniia instead.
[a park with historic architecture]

418
00:42:35,699 --> 00:42:37,919
It's closed down today.

419
00:42:38,000 --> 00:42:39,140
Even better.

420
00:42:39,400 --> 00:42:41,800
We won't go through the main entrance.

421
00:42:42,083 --> 00:42:43,820
I'll lead the way. Let's go.

422
00:42:44,220 --> 00:42:47,423
Here we go again...
Always at lunchtime.

423
00:43:07,060 --> 00:43:08,540
Okay, we're here.

424
00:43:08,680 --> 00:43:09,960
Now move backwards a little.

425
00:43:10,420 --> 00:43:13,420
<i>No entrance</i>

426
00:43:14,120 --> 00:43:15,247
Yes.

427
00:43:44,800 --> 00:43:48,520
Ladies and gentlemen, behind that fence
lies the Chornobyl zone.

428
00:43:54,860 --> 00:43:56,320
Over there, a house.

429
00:43:56,400 --> 00:43:59,400
In that very house, the poet was born.

430
00:44:12,340 --> 00:44:14,722
They are asking what are
these people doing here.

431
00:44:16,511 --> 00:44:17,560
People?

432
00:44:17,640 --> 00:44:21,520
They're used to it. It's safe on this side.
The zone starts only after the fence.

433
00:44:25,620 --> 00:44:26,784
And the horses?

434
00:44:27,270 --> 00:44:31,620
Those are wild horses. Mustangs.

435
00:44:44,680 --> 00:44:45,920
Okay, let's move on.

436
00:44:46,000 --> 00:44:47,780
We shouldn't stay here for long.

437
00:44:48,221 --> 00:44:54,160
I will now show you the place
where Danylo wrote his last poem.

438
00:46:22,400 --> 00:46:26,900
Hello, granddad! Thank you!
[with a strong accent]

439
00:46:47,580 --> 00:46:48,660
What does she want?

440
00:46:48,740 --> 00:46:51,740
Bring it on. Prytuliuk's last poem.

441
00:47:00,600 --> 00:47:05,060
In this very spot,
his last poem was written.

442
00:47:07,240 --> 00:47:09,820
Who had set this town ablaze?..

443
00:47:10,580 --> 00:47:14,280
Who had drank the blood and brains?
Causing enemies to rot,

444
00:47:14,360 --> 00:47:16,180
Gods of vengeance, are you not?..

445
00:47:20,280 --> 00:47:22,640
We had send them all to rot

446
00:47:22,923 --> 00:47:25,820
Firing steady from our Grad
[Grad = Soviet rocket launcher]

447
00:47:25,954 --> 00:47:27,694
After all the shots we've fired,

448
00:47:32,560 --> 00:47:34,480
Sat in ruins, a little tired.

449
00:47:34,840 --> 00:47:38,650
Who can read the stars and tell
Where to drill to find a well?

450
00:47:38,730 --> 00:47:40,740
We're all family, understood?

451
00:47:41,144 --> 00:47:44,960
Step ahead, if someone could.

452
00:47:45,040 --> 00:47:48,560
All is quiet but for one man,

453
00:47:51,560 --> 00:47:55,568
In his back, a deadly wound.

454
00:48:00,082 --> 00:48:01,799
Some are fallen, still we're plenty.

455
00:48:01,880 --> 00:48:03,640
Kitchen here is an ordeal.

456
00:48:03,720 --> 00:48:06,720
Step ahead who'd like to turn
Those camelthorns into a meal?

457
00:48:07,100 --> 00:48:09,780
Step ahead who'd like to try it!

458
00:48:09,860 --> 00:48:11,320
All are quiet...

459
00:48:12,560 --> 00:48:14,880
But for one man,

460
00:48:15,286 --> 00:48:18,800
In his back, a deadly wound.

461
00:48:19,474 --> 00:48:24,620
Who knows how to wash his clothes?
Who does all the household chores?

462
00:48:24,700 --> 00:48:26,500
All are quiet, of course relying

463
00:48:26,580 --> 00:48:28,230
On a man with a deadly wound.

464
00:48:28,310 --> 00:48:30,230
"Who can build a house from blocks?"

465
00:48:30,310 --> 00:48:31,520
"I can,"

466
00:48:32,620 --> 00:48:34,809
said the deadly wounded.

467
00:48:35,060 --> 00:48:36,960
"Who can sew and patch our socks?"

468
00:48:37,480 --> 00:48:38,440
"I can,"

469
00:48:38,520 --> 00:48:40,560
said the deadly wounded.

470
00:48:40,640 --> 00:48:43,560
"Who can fix a pair of shoes?"

471
00:48:43,640 --> 00:48:44,420
"I can,"

472
00:48:44,960 --> 00:48:46,659
said the deadly wounded.

473
00:48:48,974 --> 00:48:50,600
"Who can sing some pretty tunes?"

474
00:48:50,680 --> 00:48:51,560
"I can,"

475
00:48:52,180 --> 00:48:54,120
said the deadly wounded.

476
00:48:55,900 --> 00:48:58,040
"Who can bake a piece of bread?"

477
00:48:58,120 --> 00:48:59,790
"I can," said the deadly wounded.

478
00:49:00,210 --> 00:49:01,710
"Treat the wounded, bury dead?"

479
00:49:02,140 --> 00:49:04,280
"I can," said the deadly wounded.

480
00:49:04,580 --> 00:49:06,640
"Sing a child a lullaby?"

481
00:49:07,520 --> 00:49:09,640
"I can," said the deadly wounded.

482
00:49:10,180 --> 00:49:12,540
"Pray to God above the sky?"

483
00:49:12,680 --> 00:49:14,940
"I can," said the deadly wounded.

484
00:49:15,616 --> 00:49:17,256
"If you're lying, you are dead!"

485
00:49:18,560 --> 00:49:19,660
"Me?",

486
00:49:20,620 --> 00:49:22,360
the deadly wounded said.

487
00:49:22,604 --> 00:49:24,500
"I don't lie and don't you doubt it."

488
00:49:25,800 --> 00:49:27,420
"You're a stupid ass, you got it?"

489
00:49:27,500 --> 00:49:30,420
"I'll destroy you, no remorse,

490
00:49:30,500 --> 00:49:33,920
I will drown you like a puppy!
15 mins to prove your worth."

491
00:50:06,625 --> 00:50:09,020
Don't get lost, Oksana!

492
00:50:11,850 --> 00:50:14,373
Come inside, brothers.

493
00:50:43,340 --> 00:50:45,720
Any manuscripts left?
Or Sukhohryz again?

494
00:50:45,800 --> 00:50:47,720
Of course Sukhohryz.

495
00:50:50,460 --> 00:50:52,680
You said it was the last poem. Why?

496
00:50:54,900 --> 00:50:56,920
It went in print...

497
00:50:57,000 --> 00:50:58,560
the day the Afghan war started.

498
00:50:59,100 --> 00:51:01,860
If not for Nina Shans,
you know what awaited him.

499
00:51:01,940 --> 00:51:04,057
Danylo quit writing.

500
00:51:04,740 --> 00:51:05,840
Why?

501
00:51:07,200 --> 00:51:08,840
Lost the taste for it.

502
00:51:27,752 --> 00:51:29,670
Have you seen anything like this

503
00:51:29,750 --> 00:51:30,861
in America?

504
00:51:32,393 --> 00:51:35,060
Paper recycling plant.

505
00:51:35,140 --> 00:51:36,596
Produces toilet paper.

506
00:51:39,840 --> 00:51:41,940
Danylo, is this Sukhohryz?

507
00:51:42,020 --> 00:51:43,700
No, it's a prominent novelist.

508
00:51:43,780 --> 00:51:45,480
It's not Sukhohryz.

509
00:51:45,862 --> 00:51:49,790
Sukhohryz is higher up.
He's in the office.

510
00:51:50,560 --> 00:51:52,700
Oh, hey, Danylo. You still alive?

511
00:51:52,780 --> 00:51:54,520
Alive, can't you see?

512
00:51:54,600 --> 00:51:56,900
Is she filming me right now?

513
00:51:56,980 --> 00:51:59,610
She is. Americans,
you know how they are.

514
00:51:59,690 --> 00:52:03,980
They came to see how poetry
becomes toilet paper.

515
00:52:04,771 --> 00:52:07,280
Oh well. It's a complicated process.

516
00:52:08,120 --> 00:52:10,044
It's not some juvenile scribbling.

517
00:52:10,396 --> 00:52:11,900
It's physics!

518
00:52:14,169 --> 00:52:15,208
Let's go!

519
00:52:15,288 --> 00:52:18,660
Danylo, wrap this tour up, will you?

520
00:52:20,700 --> 00:52:22,220
We're taking them to lunch now.

521
00:52:23,180 --> 00:52:26,364
You, meanwhile, go find Nina Shans,
whatever it takes.

522
00:52:26,444 --> 00:52:28,060
They want to meet her.

523
00:52:28,140 --> 00:52:29,600
<i>Pavlo Shans, Prof.</i>

524
00:53:36,000 --> 00:53:37,247
Nina.

525
00:53:38,253 --> 00:53:39,120
Nina!

526
00:54:16,016 --> 00:54:17,851
This day is full of surprises.

527
00:54:17,932 --> 00:54:19,720
I still can't wrap my head around it.

528
00:54:19,800 --> 00:54:25,344
The tour keeps taking us
to various addresses from your mail.

529
00:55:27,680 --> 00:55:28,780
Happy holiday.

530
00:55:44,710 --> 00:55:46,904
Why aren't you
at lunch with the others?

531
00:55:50,687 --> 00:55:51,953
Stupid...

532
00:55:52,758 --> 00:55:53,860
Let's go.

533
00:55:54,290 --> 00:56:01,755
{\an8}<i>Dear sailors! Happy holiday.
I salute you! Safe travels.</i>

534
00:55:56,436 --> 00:56:02,332
Yours, Nina Pavlovna Shans.

535
00:56:49,820 --> 00:57:01,260
<i>Moscow, Kremlin.
Nina Shans</i>

536
00:57:45,480 --> 00:57:46,688
No one's home.

537
00:58:03,880 --> 00:58:05,160
Such a bitch.

538
00:58:08,130 --> 00:58:09,540
Nina!

539
00:58:12,620 --> 00:58:13,880
Move.

540
00:58:30,608 --> 00:58:32,166
How did you get home yesterday?

541
00:58:32,247 --> 00:58:33,614
- Yesterday?
- Yes.

542
00:58:34,662 --> 00:58:35,600
I see now.

543
00:58:35,680 --> 00:58:36,760
What do you see?

544
00:58:36,840 --> 00:58:37,889
I see now.

545
00:58:38,100 --> 00:58:40,320
On the bridge, remember?

546
00:58:40,400 --> 00:58:42,029
- Do you?
- Remember what?

547
00:58:42,513 --> 00:58:43,300
Ah.

548
00:58:43,580 --> 00:58:46,949
- What do you see?
- You don't even remember the bridge.

549
00:58:47,029 --> 00:58:48,820
I remember the park on the river.

550
00:58:48,900 --> 00:58:50,840
Are you at it again?

551
00:58:52,398 --> 00:58:54,380
Again, fighting for
the freedom of the press?

552
00:58:56,880 --> 00:58:59,980
Nina!
How many times do I have to tell you!

553
00:59:00,487 --> 00:59:02,980
Lenin has been dead for a while!

554
00:59:03,740 --> 00:59:05,500
Give him peace.

555
00:59:11,325 --> 00:59:12,640
Better tell me

556
00:59:12,876 --> 00:59:15,763
what happened in the park.

557
00:59:17,044 --> 00:59:18,794
First of all, it happened...

558
00:59:19,420 --> 00:59:20,660
not in the park,

559
00:59:23,272 --> 00:59:24,960
but on the footbridge.

560
00:59:25,505 --> 00:59:26,820
And the police...

561
00:59:27,193 --> 00:59:29,177
Is it coming back to you now?

562
00:59:29,820 --> 00:59:30,760
Who is she?

563
00:59:30,840 --> 00:59:32,320
She's American, can't you tell?

564
00:59:32,400 --> 00:59:33,920
You're into foreign chicks now?

565
00:59:34,000 --> 00:59:35,260
Why is she filming you?

566
00:59:35,340 --> 00:59:36,700
She's in love. Don't you mind.

567
00:59:36,780 --> 00:59:38,540
Tell me, what's
the city code for Lviv?

568
00:59:38,620 --> 00:59:39,941
The code is 32.

569
00:59:42,840 --> 00:59:45,480
What was that about the police?

570
00:59:45,859 --> 00:59:46,799
Aha!

571
00:59:46,880 --> 00:59:47,659
Aha!

572
00:59:47,740 --> 00:59:49,700
It's the third time I'm saving his life.

573
00:59:49,850 --> 00:59:51,330
From the police?

574
00:59:51,411 --> 00:59:52,949
What's the police
got to do with it?

575
00:59:53,030 --> 00:59:55,119
Are you mad? Are you making fun of me?

576
00:59:55,200 --> 00:59:57,545
- You don't remember, do you?
- I do!.

577
00:59:57,625 --> 01:00:00,980
- He doesn't remember
what brought him to the bridge!

578
01:00:01,060 --> 01:00:02,750
I went to get paint.

579
01:00:02,830 --> 01:00:04,600
Yes. You went to get it from Tolik.

580
01:00:04,680 --> 01:00:05,280
From Tolik.

581
01:00:05,360 --> 01:00:08,800
Of course, it was obvious when I saw you
that you're getting the paint from Tolik.

582
01:00:08,880 --> 01:00:10,280
- Enough.
- Enough what?

583
01:00:10,360 --> 01:00:12,020
I went to the bridge. Then what?

584
01:00:12,100 --> 01:00:14,110
Then what, then shmat.

585
01:00:14,191 --> 01:00:16,710
One more second and you'd be done for,
that's what.

586
01:00:17,480 --> 01:00:19,086
What's with the forehead?

587
01:00:20,125 --> 01:00:21,302
Nina, it is true?

588
01:00:21,383 --> 01:00:23,140
It is.

589
01:00:23,228 --> 01:00:25,308
If not for Sukhohryz, you'll be dead.

590
01:00:25,740 --> 01:00:27,270
Sukhohryz?

591
01:00:27,568 --> 01:00:31,372
It's warm out.
He's selling his books on the bridge.

592
01:00:39,400 --> 01:00:41,720
Okay, let's hurry up.
Let's go.

593
01:00:42,440 --> 01:00:47,720
In the car, come on.
Let's go.

594
01:00:48,740 --> 01:00:50,020
Let's go!

595
01:00:51,700 --> 01:00:54,080
Didn't they want to see
where the poet has drowned?

596
01:01:13,320 --> 01:01:15,210
It happened right here.

597
01:01:15,500 --> 01:01:17,740
He and Nina
were walking across the bridge.

598
01:01:17,820 --> 01:01:20,060
And then, police,
lifeguards, everybody...

599
01:01:20,620 --> 01:01:22,460
Right here is where it all happened.

600
01:01:22,540 --> 01:01:24,315
Right here, is where the poet died.

601
01:01:34,620 --> 01:01:35,894
Top grade poems.

602
01:01:36,425 --> 01:01:37,628
Top grade.

603
01:01:38,612 --> 01:01:41,940
Who can read the stars and tell
Where to drill to find a well?

604
01:01:42,020 --> 01:01:45,580
We're all family, understood?
Step ahead, if someone could...

605
01:01:45,660 --> 01:01:47,340
...drag us out from utter shit.

606
01:01:49,520 --> 01:01:51,100
Meet Sukhohryz.

607
01:01:51,180 --> 01:01:52,720
Sukhohryz, pleased to meet you.

608
01:01:52,800 --> 01:01:58,500
Sukhohryz, pleased to meet you.

609
01:01:58,580 --> 01:02:01,580
Take a picture of me with the poet.

610
01:02:02,060 --> 01:02:03,420
Like that.

611
01:02:10,102 --> 01:02:11,307
Americans or something?

612
01:02:11,387 --> 01:02:13,680
- Yes.
- Well, thank you.

613
01:02:13,760 --> 01:02:15,070
Will they buy the books?

614
01:02:15,151 --> 01:02:15,877
Ask them.

615
01:02:15,958 --> 01:02:20,228
Take a look. Cheap prices.
"The Art of Gambling."

616
01:02:32,510 --> 01:02:33,790
I'll be damned.

617
01:02:33,960 --> 01:02:36,880
I saved his life. Yesterday.
Right here.

618
01:02:36,960 --> 01:02:38,300
He's a genius, but an idiot.

619
01:04:44,100 --> 01:04:46,205
- Hello.
- Well, finally! How are you?

620
01:04:49,800 --> 01:04:51,840
Oh, hi. I'm good. I'm all alone.

621
01:04:53,183 --> 01:04:54,674
Hello?

622
01:04:57,360 --> 01:05:02,688
The sound of trumpet summoned me...

623
01:05:02,980 --> 01:05:04,280
(mumbles)

624
01:05:06,020 --> 01:05:10,040
The trumpet was a telephone,
The call was all a ruse.

625
01:05:10,860 --> 01:05:12,100
Hello.

626
01:06:00,520 --> 01:06:02,940
I'm calling now,

627
01:06:03,144 --> 01:06:05,624
My eyes at rest.

628
01:06:06,020 --> 01:06:09,380
I used to beg on churches' steps.

629
01:06:14,140 --> 01:06:17,215
Now I don't need your pity dime,

630
01:06:17,295 --> 01:06:19,818
I pay for every word I rhyme.

631
01:06:30,040 --> 01:06:32,750
I'd gladly pay the whole amount,

632
01:06:33,309 --> 01:06:36,059
But, see, my thoughts are on discount.

633
01:06:36,563 --> 01:06:39,400
On discount.

634
01:07:08,320 --> 01:07:10,240
Again, I hear the phone demand

635
01:07:10,540 --> 01:07:12,620
I heed it's tired shrill command.

636
01:07:12,700 --> 01:07:15,070
But I have used up all replies.

637
01:07:15,150 --> 01:07:16,600
Please say...

638
01:07:17,500 --> 01:07:19,600
Please say it's
someone else you've called.

639
01:07:22,766 --> 01:07:27,070
Please say you don't know me at all.

640
01:07:33,880 --> 01:07:34,720
Hello.

641
01:07:35,242 --> 01:07:37,640
So glad you're on the phone.

642
01:07:37,720 --> 01:07:40,720
Oh, hi. I'm good. I'm all alone.

643
01:07:55,640 --> 01:07:57,570
Last night, I didn't sleep at all.

644
01:07:57,650 --> 01:08:00,920
I stayed up, watching
the seventh route videotapes.

645
01:08:34,000 --> 01:08:35,600
Here it is, apartment 5.

646
01:08:41,072 --> 01:08:43,380
My plane leaves in three hours,

647
01:08:43,460 --> 01:08:47,460
and I had to come back
to these mysterious ruins.

648
01:08:48,200 --> 01:08:51,820
You know what I want to ask you about.

649
01:08:52,580 --> 01:08:55,940
Three envelopes, sent from this address.

650
01:08:57,068 --> 01:08:59,400
You haven't opened them. Why?

651
01:09:16,799 --> 01:09:18,399
Stay back!

652
01:09:18,479 --> 01:09:19,400
Password!

653
01:09:50,352 --> 01:09:53,360
Such a nice camera.

654
01:09:54,260 --> 01:09:55,920
I wonder if it works.

655
01:10:34,280 --> 01:10:38,020
I know that you're aware that I'm aware:

656
01:10:39,236 --> 01:10:41,634
My rope's about
to end right now and there.

657
01:10:42,020 --> 01:10:44,320
And I'm not telling you exactly where:

658
01:10:44,760 --> 01:10:48,140
You know that
I'm aware that you're aware.

659
01:10:49,080 --> 01:10:50,880
You know that I'm aware...

660
01:10:50,960 --> 01:10:52,520
...that you're aware.

661
01:10:52,600 --> 01:10:54,840
I won't be hiding from
my own damn stare.

662
01:10:55,300 --> 01:10:58,280
Won't give advice, won't help,
I wouldn't dare

663
01:10:58,760 --> 01:11:01,900
Whilst knowing
you're aware that I'm aware.

664
01:11:15,150 --> 01:11:16,258
Today?

665
01:11:17,031 --> 01:11:18,485
Now?

666
01:11:19,840 --> 01:11:22,860
"I can," said the deadly wounded.

667
01:11:47,680 --> 01:11:50,680
No, no. We must...

668
01:11:53,680 --> 01:11:55,360
What a stupid girl.

669
01:11:58,560 --> 01:12:01,600
Stop! To the airport.

670
01:12:02,040 --> 01:12:05,320
Stop!

671
01:12:05,400 --> 01:12:09,800
You're going the wrong way!

672
01:12:48,562 --> 01:12:51,252
A complete horse's ass.

673
01:12:51,780 --> 01:12:54,220
Where do you need to go?

674
01:13:44,151 --> 01:13:46,220
She says we must bury it.

675
01:13:47,454 --> 01:13:48,541
Bury what?

676
01:13:51,560 --> 01:13:52,710
A dog.

677
01:13:59,130 --> 01:14:03,078
She says some dog got hit by a car.
Have you seen it?

678
01:14:04,360 --> 01:14:05,450
I saw it.

679
01:14:06,269 --> 01:14:08,220
She says we must bury it.

680
01:14:51,566 --> 01:14:53,316
Bury it, huh!

681
01:14:57,162 --> 01:14:58,753
What a burial!

682
01:15:25,310 --> 01:15:26,780
Having dreams can be sweet.

683
01:15:27,894 --> 01:15:30,230
Having dreams can be sad.

684
01:15:30,310 --> 01:15:34,980
In the morning, they taste
Like that last cigarette.

685
01:15:36,820 --> 01:15:40,670
On the railroad tracks
Sleep is cozy and tight,

686
01:15:41,070 --> 01:15:45,200
Sky is your shiny blanket,
There's no stress on your mind.

687
01:15:46,860 --> 01:15:48,440
Sleep is deep and rewarding

688
01:15:48,660 --> 01:15:50,610
When your roof is ablaze:

689
01:15:50,690 --> 01:15:53,120
You're a reckless teenager,

690
01:15:53,200 --> 01:15:55,240
Dreams are light like a haze.

691
01:15:56,721 --> 01:15:58,360
Sleep is good while you're jumping

692
01:15:58,440 --> 01:16:00,690
Far away and high up;

693
01:16:01,025 --> 01:16:02,875
Not for everyone, true, but

694
01:16:02,955 --> 01:16:05,420
I don't want it to stop.

695
01:16:06,072 --> 01:16:08,071
Proper bed is excessive:

696
01:16:08,151 --> 01:16:09,990
Maybe too much to ask,

697
01:16:10,070 --> 01:16:13,330
But just once, try some asphalt
Or a mattress of grass.

698
01:16:15,406 --> 01:16:16,760
In the morning, I'm adding

699
01:16:16,840 --> 01:16:20,250
To my dream almanac
Children hungry for love,

700
01:16:20,330 --> 01:16:23,063
Parents not loving back.

701
01:16:24,446 --> 01:16:26,250
I am lucky like this:

702
01:16:26,330 --> 01:16:28,246
I am dreaming today

703
01:16:28,326 --> 01:16:30,590
Of that someone I've missed

704
01:16:30,670 --> 01:16:34,820
Long ago, far away.

705
01:18:09,810 --> 01:18:13,090
Dovzhenko Film Studios, 1996

